{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_noone_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600258/1930012801/0366.xml":{"full_text":"INDUSTRIAL CURB\nSTOCKS IN DEMAND\nSteel and Farm Implement\nShares Featured in Quiet\nMarket.\nBY JOHN A. CRONE.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, January 28.\u2014Industrials\ncrowded utilities and oils for leadership\nin today\u2019s dull but fairly firm curb\ntrading. Sales up to noon were 310.600\nshares, or nearly 46,000 shares less than\nIn the same period yesterday.\nAmerican Superpower, Associated\nGas Sc Electric. Brasilian Traction,\nElectric Bond Sc Share and Middle West\nUtilities led the power and light issues.\nOpening with a block of 4,000 shares.\nCities Bervice easily outdistanced the\noils. London cables telling of the com\npletion of the Standard Oil Export-\nAnglo American Oil Co. limited merger,\nfollowing deposit of more than 75 per\ncent of the latter's shares, were ex\npected. and there was no reaction.\nSteels shared the speculative spot\nlight with farm implement issues in\nthe industrial list. Republic Iron Sc\nSteel Co., new common stock featured\nearly trading. These shares, and new\npreferred, which also is being admitted\nto unlisted trading privileges, are being\nexchanged for securities of the present\nRepublic Iron Steel, Central Alloys\nSteel, Donner Steel and the Bourne\nFuller Co. Opening at 76% Republic\nIron new common within an hour rose\nto 78, before reacting around midday.\nDeere Sc Co. advanced 8 points be\nfore encountering profit taking, but\nCleveland Tractor, frequently mentioned\nin merger rumors, opened down 1%\npoints. Artificial silk shares moved in\nopposite directions, Celanese preferred\nopening up 1% points at 84%, as Tubize\nappeared down fractionally at 162\nthen dropping quickly to 159.\nNoranda Mines featured the mining\nlist both in fluctuation and frequent ap\npearances on the tape, but Falcon Lead,\none of the few penny stocks remaining\non the Curb, piled up the greatest num\nber of shares until noon, as a block of\n10,000 came out at Newmont, Hud\naon Bay and United Verde at times\npointed higher. Bunker Hill Sullivan,\nwhich a few weeks ago broke 28%\npoints on the slump in silver, appeared\nat 80. or up 5 points.\nLone Star Gas initiated the move\nment in natural gas stocks, such issues\nas the usually popular United Gas and\nDixie Gas Utilities rapidly follow\ning. Pipe lines, too. were inclined to\nclimb as favorable earning reports were\nmade public.\nBlaw Knox responded to the lift in\nannual dividend payments from $1 to\n81.50 a share. Walgreen moved at a\nfaster rate than most chain stocks as\nit advanced 1% points before meeting\nprofit taking. Thermoid, one of the\nunits of the automobile accessory in\ndustry that has sufficient other lines to\nkeep it busy, also gained. St. Regis\nPaper continued in demand.\n\nCHICAGO LIVE STOCK MAEKET\nCHICAGO, January 28 (JP> (United\nStates Department of Agriculture).\u2014\nHogs\u2014Receipts, 35,000 head, including\n13,000 direct; market mostly 10 to 20\ncents higher; top, 10.55; bulk 160-220\npounds, 10.30 to 10.50; 240-300 pounds,\n10.00 to 10.30; packing sows, 8.40 to\n9.25; pigs, 9.25 to 10.00; butchers, me\ndium to choice. 250-300 pounds, 9.50\nto 10JO; 200-250 pounds, 10.10 to 10.55;\n180-200 pounds, 10.20 to 10.55; 130-160\npounds. .60 to 10.50; packing sows, 8.15\nto 9.25; pigs, medium to choice, 90-130\npounds, 9.00 to 10.15.\nCattle\u2014Receipts, 6,500 head; calves,\nreceipts, 2.500 head; better grade fed\nsteers and yearlings steady; largely on\nshipper account; other grades slow;\ndemand narrow; bull market on she\nstock; bulls and vealers lower; best fed\nsteers, 15.15; slaughter classes, steers,\ngood to choice, 1,300-1,500 pounds, 12.25\nto 15.50; 1,100-1,300 pounds, 12.25 to\n16.00; 950-1,100 pounds, 12.50 to 16.25;\ncommon and medium, 850 pounds up,\n8.75 to 12.50. Fed yearlings, good and\nchoice, 750-950 pounds, 12.75 to 16.25.\nHeifers, good and choice, 850 pounds\ndown, 12.00 to 15.00; common and\nmedium, 7.75 to 12.50. Cows, good and\nchoice, 8.00 to 10.50; common and\nmedium, 6.75 to 8.00; low cutter and\ncutter, 5J5 to 6.75. Bulls, good and\nchoice (beef), 9.50 to 10.00; cutter to\nmedium, 7.50 to 9.60. Vealers, (milk\nfed), good and choice, 12.00 to 16.00;\nmedium. 10.00 to 12.00; cull and com\nmon, 7.50 to 10.00. Stocker and feeder\nsteers, good and choice, all weights,\n10.50 to 11.50; common and medium,\n8.25 to 10.50.\nSheep\u2014Receitps, 18,000 head; market\nvery slow; bidding, 25 or more lower\nfew fat lambs, 12.50; best held above\n13.25; fat ewes weak, 6.50 to 6.75; feed\ning lambs, nominal; lambs, good and\nchoice, 92 pounds down, 12.25 to 13.35;\nmedium, 11.50 to 12.25; common, 10.00\nto 11.50; ewes, medium to choice, 150\npounds down, 5.50 to 7.10; cull and\ncommon, 3.00 to 5.75; feeder lambs\ngood and choice, 11.50 to 12.65.\nBONDS ON THE CURB\nMARKET.\ngjlesi\u00df DOMESTIC BONDS,\nthousands. Hi*h. Low. Noon.\nAluminum Co 5\u00ab\u201952. 102 V, 102 102'/,\n11 Am G aE Ss 28 95\u2019 i 95 95\nB m E%L \u00abs 2016... 105% 105'4 105%\n15 Am Had 4'4s \u201947 97*4 97% 97%\n4Am Beat 6s \u2019IS 72 71 71\n4Apbalaeh Pow 5s \u201956 96 94% 96%\n8 Ark P ft L 5s '56. 95 95 95\n5As G*E 4%s \u20194B xw. 94% 94% 94%\n1 As GAE 4%S \u20194B ww 123% 123% 123%\n2 Also OA rs B\u20194s \u201977. 101 101 101\n4 Amo O A E 5s 79% 79% 79%\n10 As Tel Ut s\u20194s \u201944 C 99% 99% 99%\n1 Bell T Can 5s A \u201955. 100% 100% 100%\n2 Boston AMe6s m '33 101 101 101\n,2*o 101% 101% 101%\n1 Cent St El 5%s \u201954.. 74% 74% 75%\nCent 8t Bis 48 71% 71% 71%\n8 Cities Ser Pw 5%s \u201952 86% 86% 86%\n1 \u00a3**V* 21 111 .7* 41 107 107 107\n2 A \u201947 105% 105% 105 V,\n\u00a3?i? OO \u00ab%l A \u201937 ww 75 75 75\n1 Edl* Elec BOS 5* 99% 99% 99%\nlOPedera l Wat 5%s \u201954 92 92% 92%\n1 2 restone T 5s 42... 92 92 92\n4 Pis L 54 87 86 87\n18 Gen Theat Eq 6s '44 116% 116% 116%\n5 Gen Wat Wk 6s B \u201934 95 95 95\n7\u00a3eo;*ja P\u00b0w 5s \u201967.. 95% 95