 Ch pt pf (3).. 1 83 83 83 33\n18% 14% United Corp war.... 13 18 18 17% 17%\nUnit El Ser pur war. 10 r\n30% 19% United Gas Co 138 29% 29% 28% 28%\n38% 29% Unit LtAPwr A(6oe) 79 36% 37 36% 36%\n101 97% Utd Lt A Pops 6 100% 100% 100% 100%\n26% 14 US Dairy B 2 15 16% 15 16%\n21 19 U S Elec Pwr ww.... 18 19% 20% 19% 20%\n25 22% US Finishing (|2).. 1 23 23 23 23\n22 17% US Foil B(l) 8 21% 21% 20% 20%\n17% 14 US Lines pf 9 16% 15% 16% 16%\n7% 6% U 8 Shares Fin 2 7% 7% 7% 7%\n3V* 3 USA Interntl Sec... 1 3V\u00ab 3V* 3% 3%\n68 60% US AlnSctf (2%).. 7 64% 66% 64% 66%\n12% 11 Unit Verde Ext (4).. 3 11% 11% 11% 11%\nft Unity Gold. 2\n2% 2% Utah Apex (50c).... 1,2% 2% 2% 2%\n19% 14% Utility Pw A Lt(al). 11 18 18% 18 18\n26% 24% Util Alndpf 8 26% 26% 25% 25%\n14% 10% Utility Equities 46 14% 14% 14% 14%\n96% 93% Vacuum Oil (t 4%).. 4 96% 96% 96 96\n9 8 Vick Fin Corp 11 8% 8% 8% 8%\n61 54 Walgreen Co 21 68% 60 58% 59%\u2019\n11 10 Walker (H)(1) 6 10% 10% 10% 10%\nWalker Mining 14% 4% 4% 4%\n62 62 Welch Q Juice t1%.. 6 62 66 62 66\n_ WendenCopper....* 4 _ _\nBUSINESS REVIVAL\nSEEN IN EUROPE\nV\nLow World Money Rates Are\nFactor in Improved Con\nditions Abroad.\n1 Special Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, January 28.\u2014Cable dis\npatches to The Business Week give the\n1 following swift survey of business abroad\nfor the week ending January 25;\nEurope.\u2014All Europe anticipates a\nbusiness revival following six months\nof uncertainty culminating in the au\nspicious settlement at The Hague, con\ncurrent with low world money rates.\nThe probable Infusion of international\ncapital Is welcomed. With difficulties\nover, reparations problems In Eastern\nEurope Ironed out, the way is prepared\nfor regular and more active trading,\ndespite the economic weakness of some\ncountries and unemployed surpluses in\nothers.\nObservers cite as favorable factors:\nRecent systematic development of in\ndustrial and business organization, the\nextent of physical productive equipment,\nthe degree of operating efficiency, last\nyear's record industrial and agricultural\ntrade volume, public purchasing power\nand wages\u2014generally higher than ever\nIn history. Because volume of flexibil\nity of credit are not commensurate with\nthe business expansion of the last three\nyears, It is considered the single dom\ninant factor entailing danger and par\ntial business relapse.\nGreat Britain's Condition.\nGreat Britain.\u2014Year\u2019s trade deficit is\n8 per cent greater than 1928, due to\nhigher Imports of Industrial raw ma\nterials and relatively smaller expansion\nof exports of manufactures. Coal ship\nments, however, increased, nearly equal\ning value of outgoing Iron and steel\ngoods, and exports of shoes, paper,\nmotor cycles and automobiles estab\nlished records. Textile exports fell be\nlow last year\u2019s slump.\nRecent improvement of business is\nmirrored in economists\u2019 tabulation of\n400 companies which showed increased\nprofits in the last quarter, notwithstand\ning some large failures and the stock\ncrash. These tabulations also indicate\nthe tendency to Increase dividend dis\ntributions, preferred dividends averag\ning s'/ 2 per cent, common lOVa per cent\nand debentures 5 per cent. Cabinet\nMinister Thomas intimates that the\nCity and Bank of England are prepared\nto finance deserving Industrial ration\nalizations. a move which implies a re\nversal of policies.\nFrance. \u2014American oil interests active\nin the French market plan co-operative\nprogram to distribute effectively behind\nthe rising protective tariff. Plan allo\ncates to Gulf Oil 25 per cent participa\ntion; to Atlantic, 15 per cent; to Stand\nard, 60 per cent. Each will observe\nthese quotas in furnishing crude oil for\nrefining and distribution.\nGermany\u2019s Trade Balance.\nGermany\u2014Year\u2019s favorable trade\nbalance of $12,000,000, just announced,\ncompares with a deficit of $300,000,000\nlast year and $500,000,000 in 1927. The\nfavorable balance is due chiefly to the\nenlargement of exports, which is an\nIndispensable offset to reparations out\ngo. Rapid expansion of French short\nterm credits is noted. Railways, al\nlocated to the Government by Hague\nagreements, expect to benefit by a\nlower loan rate than was obtainable\nindependently. Automobile tire quotas\nin the German market are allocated:\nThirteen per cent participation to the\nUnited States, 45 per cent to contin\nental exporters, 26 per cent to German\nDunlop, equal participation in the\nbalance to six others. The Soviet tire\ntrust is left out. Completely reorgan\nized, Opel-General Motors resumes\nproduction.\nHolland\u2014Rubber restriction again at\ntempted. Fresh plan advanced as basis\nfor discussion with representatives of\nBritish rubber interests proposes estab\nlishment of a participating fund \u2014plant-\ners contributing 20 guilders per ton,\nnatives 2 Dutch cents a kilogram\u2014the\nrated production contributions to be\nconfiscated if the prescribed quota is\nexceeded.\nAustria\u2014Deep satisfaction and relief\nfollow announcement of annulment of\nreparation obligations, opening the way\nfor $100,000,00 construction loan which\nwill give country fresh start industrially.\nHungary\u2014Business men are satisfied\nwith the settlement whereby rtparations\nwill be devoted to reimbursement of\nowners of sequestered agrarian property\nin ceded territories until 1943, when\nfurther reparations \u25a0will represent only\n1 per cent of the budget.\nScandinavia\u2014ln Sweden the discount\nrate is reduced; Industrial activity con\ntinues on top of record .year, with\nhighest post-war trade balance.\nIn Norway, the whaling season yields\nincome estimated at 105,000,000 crowns,\ncompared with 1928 record of 68,000,-\n000. Fishing netted 81,000,000 crowns\nabove the normal annual valuation.\nPoland\u2014New Bartel government in\ncludes renewed consideration of the\nHarriman electrification project.\nRussia\u2014The government is exporting\nwheat despite a shortage. Some\nobservers interpret this to Indicate the\npressing need for foreign exchange,\nothers that it is simply expedient to\navoid difficult long train hauls within\nthe country.\nGRAIN MARKET.\nCHICAGO, January 28 JP \u2014ynder\na wave of selling, wheat prices today\nbroke to below any recent bottom level,\nbut afterward rallied.\nWeakness of the rye market here and\nof wheat values at Winnipeg were out\nstanding bearish factors. A leading\nspeculative holder of contracts for fu\nture deliveries of rye was a heavy\nseller, and dispatches were at hand\nsaying that not within memory has\nthere been such a distracted state of\nthings in the German rye market as\nprevails at present owing to a big ex\nportable surplus both in Germany and\nPoland.\nWheat closed irregular at cent a\nbushel below yesterday\u2019s finish to Vi\ncent over, corn closed cent off to\nV 4 cent up, oats i/a cent to cent\ndown, and provision varying from 5\ncents setback to a rise of 15 cents.\nHigh. Low. Close.\n1 25% 123'. 1.25%\nJuly 1.27 1.25% 1.26%\n1 28% 1.27% 1.28%\nMarch 57% .88% .87%\nJuly .92% .92% 92*t\nSeptember 93% .93 .93%\nMarch 45% .44 .44%\nMay 46% .45% .48%\nRYE- 441 44\nMarch 91% .89 .91%\nMay 90% .88% .89%\nJu J y *W\u00ab 89 87 .89\nLARD\u2014\nJanuary 10.50 10.40 10.40\nF. W. WOOLWOBTH CO.\nNEW YORK, January 28 (/?).\u2014The\nnet profits of the F. W. Woolworth Co.\nfor 1929 amounted to $35,664,252, equal\nto $3.66 a share on the 9,750,000 $lO par\nshares, compared with $35,385,606, or\n$9.07 a share on 3,900,000 $25 par\nshares.\nThe number of stores in operation at\nthe end of 1929 totaled 1,825, as against\n1,725 at the end of 1928.\nThe company\u2019s balance sheet shows\ncurrent assets of $51,501,638 and current\nliabilities of $3,135,117, leaving a work\ning capital of $48,367,521 at the end of\n1929. The working capital at the end\nof 1928 totaled $50,645,743.\n--Prev. m-, Stock and Sales-\nH \u00aba.,S lvUlen J? ate Add OoTOpen. Hlth. Low. Close.\n.18%, 1614 WlUiam*RC (1.40). 6 18% 18% 18% 18%\n66 61 Wilson .Tones (3).... 1 64 64 64 64\n4% 3% Winter (BenJ) 14% 4% 4*4 444\nUIGHTS. Expire.*\n1% 1% Baltimore* Ohio.. Mar. 11 128 1% 1% 1% 1%\n114 1 Crocker Wheeler ...Feb. 24 2 11 11\nUSES OF STEEL INCREASED\nBY INVENTION OF ALLOYS\nCorporation Ch airman Cites Benefit to\nIndustry Through Gain in Demand\n-for Various New Products.\nBY JOHN F. SINCLAIR.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, January 28.\u20141 n the\nNation\u2019s Business tor January F. j.\nGriffiths, chairman of the Central Alloy\nSteel Corporation, head of the research\ndivision of the Republic Steel Corpora\ntion, says:\n\u201cFifty per cent of the steel used In\nautomobiles Is alloy and the average\nweight per car has been reduced to less\nthan 30 per cent of what it was.\"\nTJhe use of steel has expanded rapidly\nsiqpe the development of steel alloy,\nfor it has increased flexibility and en\ndurance. It has solved the problem of\nrust through \u201cstainless steel.\u201d The use\nof rust-resisting alloy for freight cars\nhas reduced the weight of each car by\none ton. A new alloy process known as\n\u201cnitriding\" has produced the hardest\nknown metal surface.\n\u201cIt has been found that every time\nthe price of a special steel is reduced 1\ncent a pound the market for it is\nwidened by 10 per cent,\u201d says this in\nternational authority on alloy steel.\nThe steel industry, already huge, is\nonly in its infancy.\nAn industry that has a monopoly\nupon one form of service or another is\napt to become stale. A new invention\noften wakes it up and forces it to ex\ntend its research and to speed up its\nlagging interest. Fine tonic for most\nmonopolies.\nNot long ago a leading member of the\nartificial ice industry, in speaking of the\neffect that mechanical refrigerators\nhave had upon the industry, said that\nit had awakened the industry as to its\npossibilities and caused a general clean\nup in the natural ice industry by cut\nting out waste and rendering better\nservice. Both groups prospered!\nThe gas industry suffered a severe\nblow when electricity became general\nfor lighting purposes. Up to then,\nlighting had been almost its sole \u201cmeans\nof support,\u201d but the cutting off of this\nmarket made the industry realize that\nit would have to find other markets or\nquit the field. So it turned to the field\nof cooking.\nRealizing the advantages gas had\nover other forms of heating energy, the\nindustry pushed its sale for use in\nhouseheating and in industrial processes.\nThe extent to which it has been suc\ncessful may be readily seen from its\nsales .for 1929, which were greater by\n8.1 per cent than they were in 1928.\nWhile the domestic- sales, chiefly cook\ning, increased by only 4.4 per cent,\nsales for house heating purposes in\ncreased 51.7 per cent and for industrial\npurposes 11.8 per cent.\nAlthough an industry may suffer\nseverely from a substitute entering into\nits field, if it is successful in clearing\nout the dead wood, reducing waste and\nincreasing research, the new competi\ntion often proves to be a blessing in\ndisguise.\nWill Germany, poor in natural re\nsources and raw materials, become\neventually a free trade country like\nEngland?\nMany of her industries are kept up\nCorporation News\nNEW YORK, January 28.\u2014The fol\nlowing is today\u2019s summary of important\ncorporation news prepared by Standard\nStatistics Co., Inc., New York, for the\nAssociated Press:\nNews Trend.\nEarly estimate of daily domestic\ncrude oil production for the week Jan\nuary 25 is placed at 2,815,128 barrels,\na decrease of 47,679 barrels from the\nprevious week. The average price of\ncrude oil in 10 producing fields during\nthe week was $1,575 a barrel, the same\nas in the preceding week; average price\na year ago was $1,693 a barrel. Gaso\nline prices at four principal refineries\ndeclined last week to 7.375 cents a gal\nlon from 7.50 cents in the preceding\nweek. Service station prices at 10\nprincipal markets remained at 19.22\ncents a gallon.\nRailroad earnings for December with\nbut few exceptions continue to make an\nunfavorable comparison with the like\nmonth of 1928. Earnings of the first\n25 railroads to report show a decline\nin net operating Income of 18 per cent\nfrom December, 1928. For the full\nyear, however, these same roads show\nan Increase in net operating Income of\n5.8 per cent from the year 1928.\nThe Companies.\nAmerican Brown Boverl expects defi\ncit for fourth quarter of 1929. Arundel\nCorporation earned $4.15 in year 1929\nvs. $3.16 in 1928. Atlas Stores declares\ncommon stock dividend of 1% per\ncent and regular quarterly dividend of\n25 cents on common stock. Baltimore\nAc Ohio net, December, 1929, off 33.9\nper cent; year 1929 off 0.4 per cent\nfrom 1928.\nRepublic Steel Corporation details\nof merger of this company with Central\nAlloy Steel Corporation, Donner Steel\nCo., Baurn-Fuller Co. and Trumbull-\nCliffs into new Republic Steel Corpora\ntion, Include issuing of $55,000,000 of\n6 per cent cumulative convertible pre\nferred SIOO par stock and 1,985,144\nshares of no par common stock which\nwill be exchanged for preferred and\ncommon stock of these companies.\nThere will also be outstanding funded\ndebt assumed of $59,059,400, and $5,-\n000.000 of 6 per cent cumulative pre\nferred stock of Trumbull-Cliffs Furnace.\nRutland Railroad, December, 1929,\nnet off 35.8 per cent; 12 months, 1929,\nup 6 per cent from 1928.\nSweets Co. of America earned $1.22\nin year 1929 against $1.06 in 1928.\nTexas As Pacific, December, 1929,\noff 48.5 per cent: year 1929, down 15.9\nper cent from 1928. Earned $12.76 in\nyear 1929 against $17.50 in 1928.\nUnited States Rubber to supply 1930\nmotor coach tire requirements to De\ntroit street railways; rent and service,\n$424.87 a day on mileage basis.\nWheeling Sc Lake Erie Railroad,\nDecember, 1929, net, off 50.7 per cent:\nyear 1929, net, up 2.8 per cent from\n1928.\nWhite Eagle Oil Sc Refining stock\nholders approve sale of assets to\ni\nSTOCK AND BOND MARKET AVERAGES\nProm Yesterday\u2019* 8:30 Kdltlos.\nBr the Associated Press.\nSTOCKS.\nSO 20 jo 99\nIndustrials. Rails. Utilities. Total.\n?\u00b0**y J 7 9 181.9 222.6 176.5\n7 133.1 228.2 176.5\nWeek 167.7 130.4 215.1 170 0\nr 136.0 213.2 201.3\nTwo years MB.. 146.3 120.0 132.1 139.6\nThree years aco, weekly aver. .105.6 105.8 101.3 1940\nHlfh (1929) 252.8 167.8 353 1\n(m\u00bb) uu ntj 5,21\nTotal sales, 3,458,020 shares.\nBONDS.\nIS 10 10 39\n_ _ Industrials. Rails. Utilities. Total.\nToday 92.6 194.5 97.9 98.3\nPrertsus day 92.7 194.7 98.0 98 5\nWeek aco 92.6 105.3 98.4 osi\nTwo years aye. 97.4 108.9 100.6 102. S\nThree years aco, weekly aver.. 95.7 195.0 98.4 99 7\nH!*h (1929) 95.3 106.0 99.8 999\nl /OW (1929) 99.4 190.8 90.0 96 3\nTotal sales (par value), $7,717,999. 8,5\n(Copyrlsht. 1830, Standard Statistics Oo.)\nHigh. Low. Dividend Rate. Add 00. Open. Hi\u00abh. Low Close\nSV\u00bb 2% So. Cal. Edison.... Apr. It S 3 3 3 3\u2019\n.10 .01 Trans Corp Mar. 5 12 .06 .06 03 03\nannual payment* I** 1 don,r bM#d #B ,Mt eesei\ncash kislesfc. a Parable is\nsash or stoek. hParaMa in stock. operable in prsisrrsd sttjsk.\nFINANCIAL\nnow by importing raw materials, de\nveloping them into manufactured prod\nucts and sending them out to all parts\nof the world.\nThe porcelain industry is an example.\nGermany has 300 factories, employing\n60,000 workers, and has been developed\nlargely in Saxony, Bavaria and Silesia,\nspecializing in household decoratlves\nand electro-porcelain.\nThe raw materials come from three\ndifferent countries \u2014china clay is ob\ntained from Czechoslovakia, feldspar\nfrom Scandinavia and the quartz from\nGermany itself.\nBut the thrifty Germans have ham\nmered it into one of their most prosper\nous industries.\nWhen the Czar of Russia was killed,\nhe had large sums of money deposited\nin various banks throughout the world\n\u2014in Berlin, Paris, London and New\nYork. The Czar, well advised in busi\nness, did not put all his money into one\nbasket.\nFrank Gardner, Philadelphia-born\nmining engineer, whose career ante\ndates even that of John Hays Ham\nmond in uncovering the great mining\ntreasures of the world, was a close\nfriend of the Czar. He was trusted by\nthe family.\nThis money, still on deposit, is wait\ning for its legal claimants. This Ameri\ncan engineer, a friend of the family,\nhas been given power of attorney to\nsecure the money. But who can give\na legal proof of the Czar\u2019s death?\nTwo sisters of the Czar still are liv\ning. One, Grand Duchess Xenia, lives\nat Windsor Palace, near London. She\nis the wife of the Grand Duke Alex\nander.\nThe other sister is Grand Duchess\nOlga, who married a Russian cavalry\nofficer, and who lives at Copenhagen,\nthe home of the dowager empress.\nFrank Gardner has had many hard\nand difficult tasks to solve in his long\nand eventful life. But none more diffi\ncult than this one.\nA. R. Erskine, president of the Stude\nbaker Corporation, believes that the\nautomobile Industry has been so com\npletely Integrated into the economic so\ncial life of the Nation that production\nfrom now on will sustain a very definite\nmathematical relation to the growth of\npopulation, wealth and income of the\ncountry and to the volume of commer\ncial and industrial activity throughout\nthe world.\nHe believes that the average annual\noutput of 5,000,000 cars in the United\nStates will be an established fact in\nthe next 10 years.\nTo take care of the annual replace\nments, 3,750,000 will have to be pro\nduced. In 1928 replacement sales\nreached 2,450,000 while annual exports\nnow reach 500,000.\nWhen the foreign business of Ameri\ncan car manufacturers reaches 40 per\ncent of the output, and Mr. Erskine be\nlieves that it will eventually, then the\nproblem of the American car manufac\nturers will be a relatively simple one.\n(Copyright, 1930, North American Newspaper\nAlliance.)\nStandard Oil of New York, in exchange\nfor stock of latter; basis BVfc shares of\nSocony for each 10 shares White Eagle.\nBlaw Knox declares quarterly divi\ndend of 37*4 cents, placing common\nstock on $1.50 annual basis; formerly\npaid $2.\nBohn Aluminum St Brass earned\n$7.43 in year 1969 against $9.10 in 1928.\nBuffalo, Rochester St Pittsburgh, net,\nDecember. 1929, up 9.9 per cent; 12\nmonths, 1929, up 5 per cent from 1928.\nBuffalo St Susquehanna Railroad,\nnet, December, 1929, off 16.3 per cent;\nyear 1929, up 7.1 per cent over 1928.\nChicago, Milwaukee. St. Paul St\nPacific Railroad, December, 1929, net,\noff 34.2 per cent; year 1929, net, off\n9.6 per cent from 1928.\nCleveland, Cincinnati, Chicago St St.\nLouis Railroad, net, December, 1929,\noff 56.4 per cent; year 1929, up 1.9 per\ncent over 1928.\nDelaware St Hudson Railroad net De\ncember, 1929, off 65.2 per cent; year\n1929, up 6.2 per cent.\nDelaware, Lackawanna St Western,\nDecember, 1929. net off 6.4 per cent;\nyear 1929, up 2.3 per cent from 1928.\nFox Theater stockholder institutes\nreceivership action against this com\npany.\nGeneral Refractories declared extra\ndividend of 25 cents and regular quar\nterly dividend of $1 on common stock.\nGreat Northern Railroad net Decem\nber, 1929, $1,950,135, against $946,546,\na year ago; year 1929, net up 3.9 per\ncent over 1928.\nGulf, Mobile St Southern Railroad\nnet December, 1929, off 27 per cent;\n12 months 1929 up 9.9 per cent from\n1928.\nHawaiian Pineapple earned $5.08 in\nyear 1929, against $3.80 in 1928.\nInternational Great Northern Rail\nroad, December, 1929, net up 9.6 per\ncent; year 1925, off 13.6 per cent.\nMinneapolis St St. Louis Railroad net\nDecember, 1929, $33,034, against $4,178\nyear ago; year 1929, $1,867,016, against\n$522,277 in 1928.\nMissouri, Kansas Texas Railroad\nearned $5.10 in year 1929, against $4.61\nin 1928.\nMissouri Pacific, December, 1929, net\noff 11.7 per cent; year 1929, up 15 per\ncent from 1928. Earned $10.42 in year\n1929, against $7.15 in 1928.\nNashville, Chattanooga St St. Louis\nRailroad, net December, 1929, up 128.9\nper cent; year 1929 up 14.2 per cent.\nPennsylvania Railroad,. December,\n1929, net off 36.8 per cent; 12 months,\n1929, up 14.4 per cent over 1928.\nPowdrell St Alexander, declared extra\ndividend of 37 >4 cents and quarterly\ndividends of 87 >4 cents on common\nstock.\n\nBANK CLEARINGS.\nNEW YORK, January 28 (Special).\u2014\nNew York bank clearings, today,\n$1,182,000,000; a year ago, $1,991,000,000.\nNew York bank balances, today, $142,-\n000,000; a year ago. $187,000,000.\nNew York Federal reserve credit bal\nances, today, $137,000,000; a year ago,\n$156,000,000.\nA-15\nREPARATIONS LOAN\nPROSPECT IS GOOD\nMarket for Foreign Dollar\nBond Issues Has Im\nproved Recently.\ni\nBY CHARLES F. SPEARE.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nWALL STREET, NEW YORK. Janu\nary 28.\u2014From the standpoint of floating\nsupply the market for foreign dollar\nbonds is in a stronger position today\nthan in the past t'ao years to receive\nthe first installment of the proposed\nreparations loan.\nOn the other hand, it is less favorably\nsituated with respect to prices than It\nhad been before pending the flotation\nof what might be termed a pivotal\npiece of European financing in the form\nof dollars.\nWith easier money conditions in this\ncountry, however, it is the feeling of\nthose bankers who will head the syndl\nj CBt\u00ae to be formed for the reparation\nloan that the price situation can be\nimproved. Already this is taking place\nin those foreign bonds that have the\nmost intimate connection with the\nreparations loan. This includes German\nissues of the municipal type and also\nthe securities of institutions over which\nthe Reich exercises more or less control.\nAll of these bonds have advanced sub\nstantially since the early part of the\nyear.\n1929 Financing Small.\nFigures presented by the finance divi\nsion of the Department of Commerce\nsuggest the low ebb in foreign financing\nduring 1929. The total number of new\nissues that year and the dollar amount\ni represented by them was the smallest\nsince 1924. less than half the new\ncapital for foreign use was raised In\ni 1928 CoUntry Ixl 1929 com P* r with\nAn analysis of the record of foreign\nloans since 1916, when France and\ni r itain became large borrowers\nl in this country and their securities were\nsomewhat timidly presented to the\nAmerican investing public for approval,\nshows that the Doom time for such\noperations was between 1924 and 1928.\nIt was at the latter end of this period\nthat the market became so saturated\nwith foreign dollar issues that it crum\nbled and practically all of the offerings\nin the first half of 1928 went to a sub\n-1 stantial discount from the subscription\nprices.\nIn this five-year period there were\napproximately 1.000 different foreign\nissues, including loans to governments,\ncities and provinces, to industrial cor\nporations, to public utilities, to banks\nand even to religious organizations.\nThey represented a total par value of\napproximately $7,000,000,000. The year\nof greatest volume in loans was 1927,\nwhen nearly $1,600,000,000 came into\nthe American market.\nBetween 1916 and the end of 1923\nthere were about 500 different issues\nrepresented by a par value of slightly\nunder $5,500,000,000. These included\nmany of the choice 8 per cent loans\ntoe strongest of the European\ncredits and of which many have since\nbeen retired.\nExcess Largely Absorbed.\nCraning down to 1929, it is found that\nthe total number of new issues in that\nyear was only 132 and that the dollar\namount was $715,000,000. However, a\nvery high percentage of this was for\nCanadian account. Few loans were\nmade during the year to Europe or to\nSouth and Central America and less\nthan $70,000,000 directly to govern\nments.\nThe situation today is that the ex\ncess of loans in 1927 and in 1928 has\nbeen quite generally absorbed, and there\nare few outstanding weak accounts of\nsuch loans in dealers\u2019 hands. This places\nthe market In a sotrnd technical posi\ntion to receive additional bonds when\nthe first portion of the reparations loan\nis out of the way and foreign govern\nments and foreign corporations get con\nsent from their bankers to resume ne\ngotiations along the lines that were\nabandoned in 1929.\nrtf\nNEW YORK COTTON.\nNEW YORK, January 28 (A\u00bb).\u2014Cot\nton opened steady today at a decline of\n1 point to an advance of 2 points. There\nwas a little selling under the relatively\neasy showing of Liverpool and the de\ncline in Bombay, but the offerings were\nquite readily absorbed by trade buying\nor covering and the initial irregularity\nwas followed by a fairly steady market.\nMay, after selling off to 17.28, rallied\nto 17.32 and the general list was about\nnet unchanged to 3 points higher at the\nend of the first half hour. Business was\nonly moderately active, but there was\na little more trade buying in evidence\nand probably covering on an idea that\nthe demand would improve as prices\napproached a parity with farm loan\nvalues in the South.\nThe weekly trade report of the New\nYork Cotton Exchange estimating\nworld's consumption of American lint\ncotton at 1.042,000 bales for December,\nagainst 1,188,000 last year came in for\nsome bearish comment and may have\nbeen a factor on some of the earlier\nselling.\nNEW YORK BANK STOCKS.\nBanks.\nBid. Asked.\nAmerica 133 13*\nAmer Union #5 105\nBk of U 8 un 85 88\nBk Yorktown 3to\nBroadway Nat 119 138\nBryant Park 45 55\nCentral Nat 138 134\nChase 185 187\nChat Phenix 133 135\nCity 333'a 3351%\nColumbus 157\nCommercial 490 500\nFifth Ave 3900 3100\nPirst National 5300 5350\nQrace 600\nHarbor State 85 75\nHafrlman 1375 1415\nIndustrial 300 335\nInter-Madison 33 40\nLebanon iso\nLefcourt 130 140\nLiberty 100 110\nManhat Co 13514 137\nMelrose 330 330\nMerchants 100 135\nMidtown 33 43\nPenn Exch 75 85\nPort Morris 35 45\nPrisco State 300 475\nPublic 135 138\nSeward 134 133\nSixth Ave 180 170\n